Problem Statement
From a list, print all numbers greater than 10.


#Solution:-
Java 8 Streams filter collections using a Predicate, chaining filter with > 10 before terminal forEach to print matching integers. This declarative style processes lazily, only evaluating needed elements.

#Step-by-Step Logic:-
Create stream from list via stream(). Chain filter(num -> num > 10) to retain elements > 10.
Terminate with forEach(System.out::println) to print survivors on separate lines.
​

#Complete Implementation:-

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class PrintGreaterThanTen {
    public static void printGreaterThanTen(List<Integer> numbers) {
        numbers.stream()
               .filter(num -> num > 10)
               .forEach(System.out::println);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(5, 12, 8, 15, 3, 20);
        printGreaterThanTen(numbers);
    }
}

#Output:-
Prints only 12, 15, 20. Lambda predicate is concise; method reference handles printing.
​
#Thought Process:-
Build from source stream, add intermediate filter for condition (predicate returns boolean). Select forEach terminal for side-effect printing, avoiding collection if unneeded. Lazy evaluation skips non-matches early.
​
#Edge Cases Analysis:-
Empty list: No output, no exception.​
Null list: NullPointerException on stream(); precondition null-check.
All ≤10: Nothing prints.
Null elements: filter skips (null > 10 false); println safe if reached.
Exactly 10: Filtered out (>10 strict).
Negatives/large: Negatives fail; INT_MAX fine, no overflow in comparison.
Large lists: O(n) sequential scan; parallel for >10^6 if order irrelevant, but printing unordered.
